  lectureDescription: "<h1>Lecture Summary: RPCs</h1><p>In this lecture, we learned
    how to use <strong>RPCs </strong>(Remote Procedure Calls) to ensure the server
    handles spawning objects, solving the issue from the previous lecture. RPCs allow
    clients to <strong>send messages </strong>to the server (or vice versa) to run
    specific functions.</p><p>We added an <strong>[Rpc(SendTo.Server)]</strong> attribute
    to the ClickedOnGridPositionRpc function, ensuring it only executes on the server.
    We also renamed the function to include \"<strong>Rpc</strong>\" at the end,
    as required. To enable RPC functionality, we updated the script to inherit from
    <strong>NetworkBehaviour </strong>instead of MonoBehaviour and ensured the object
    had a <strong>NetworkObject </strong>component.</p><p>After implementing and
    testing, the client now sends a message to the server when clicking, and the
    server spawns the object, maintaining <strong>server authority.</strong> Next,
    we\u2019ll address synchronizing the object\u2019s position using the <strong>NetworkTransform
    </strong>component.</p>\r\n<p>C# Course - Attributes [10:37:28] <a href=\"https://youtu.be/qZpMX8Re_2Q?t=38248\"
    target=\"_blank\" style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">https://youtu.be/qZpMX8Re_2Q?t=38248</a></p>\r\n##REF##video_small,
    qZpMX8Re_2Q, Learn C# FREE Tutorial Course Beginner to Advanced! [12 HOURS]##REF##\r\n"
